# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: wireguard
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:wireguard/chacha20-poly1305] The two building blocks of the construction, the algorithms Poly1305 and ChaCha20, were both independently designed, in 2005 and 2008, by Daniel J.
[src:wireguard/chacha20-poly1305] In March 2013, a proposal was made to the IETF TLS working group to include Salsa20, a winner of the eSTREAM competition to replace the aging RC4-based ciphersuites.
[src:wireguard/chacha20-poly1305] A discussion followed in the IETF TLS mailing list with various enhancement suggestions, including using Chacha20 instead of Salsa20 and using a universal hashing based MAC for performance.
[src:wireguard/chacha20-poly1305] Shortly after the IETF's adoption of ChaCha20 and Poly1305 for TLS, the combined AEAD mode was added to OpenSSH via the`chacha20-poly1305@openssh.com` authenticated encryption cipher but kept the original 64-bit counter and 64-bit nonce for the ChaCha20 algorithm.
[src:wireguard/chacha20-poly1305] In 2015, the AEAD algorithm was standardized in RFC 7539 and in RFC 7634 to be used in IPsec.
[src:wireguard/chacha20-poly1305] The same year, it was integrated by Cloudflare as an alternative ciphersuite.
[src:wireguard/chacha20-poly1305] In 2016 RFC 7905 describes how to use it in the TLS 1.2 and DTLS 1.2 protocols.
[src:wireguard/chacha20-poly1305] In June 2018, RFC 7539 was updated and replaced by RFC 8439.
[src:wireguard/chacha20-poly1305] The ChaCha20-Poly1305 algorithm takes as input a 256-bit key and a 96-bit nonce to encrypt a plaintext, with a ciphertext expansion of 128-bit (the tag size).
[src:wireguard/chacha20-poly1305] In the ChaCha20-Poly1305 construction, ChaCha20 is used to derive a key stream that is XORed with the plaintext.
[src:wireguard/chacha20-poly1305] The ciphertext and the associated data is then authenticated using a variant of Poly1305 that first encodes the two strings into one.
[src:wireguard/chacha20-poly1305] The way that a cipher and a one time authenticator are combined is precisely identical to AES-GCM construction in how the first block is used to seed the authenticator and how the ciphertext is then authenticated with a 16-byte tag.
[src:wireguard/chacha20-poly1305] The main external difference with ChaCha20 is its 64 byte (512 bit) block size, in comparison to 16 bytes (128 bit) with both AES-128 and AES-256.
[src:wireguard/chacha20-poly1305] The larger block size enables higher performance on modern CPUs and allows for larger streams before the 32 bit counter overflows.
[src:wireguard/chacha20-poly1305] The XChaCha20-Poly1305 construction is an extended 192-bit nonce variant of the ChaCha20-Poly1305 construction, using XChaCha20 instead of ChaCha20.
[src:wireguard/chacha20-poly1305] When choosing nonces at random, the XChaCha20-Poly1305 construction allows for better security than the original construction.
[src:wireguard/chacha20-poly1305] The draft attempt to standardize the construction expired in July 2020.
[src:wireguard/chacha20-poly1305] Salsa20-Poly1305 and XSalsa20-Poly1305 are variants of the ChaCha20-Poly1305 and XChaCha20-Poly1305 algorithms, using Salsa20 and XSalsa20 in place of ChaCha20 and XChaCha20.
[src:wireguard/chacha20-poly1305] They are implemented in NaCl and libsodium but not standardized.
[src:wireguard/chacha20-poly1305] The variants using ChaCha are preferred in practice as they provide better diffusion per round than Salsa.
[src:wireguard/chacha20-poly1305] ChaCha20 can be replaced with its reduced-round variants ChaCha12 and ChaCha8, yielding ChaCha12-Poly1305 and ChaCha8-Poly1305.
[src:wireguard/chacha20-poly1305] The same modification can be applied to XChaCha20-Poly1305.
[src:wireguard/chacha20-poly1305] These are implemented by the RustCrypto team and not standardized.
[src:wireguard/chacha20-poly1305] ChaCha20-Poly1305 is used in IPsec, SSH, TLS 1.2, DTLS 1.2, TLS 1.3, WireGuard, S/MIME 4.0, OTRv4 and multiple other protocols and implemented in OpenSSL and libsodium.
[src:wireguard/chacha20-poly1305] Additionally, the algorithm is used in the backup software Borg in order to provide standard data encryption and in the copy-on-write filesystem Bcachefs for the purpose of optional whole filesystem encryption.
[src:wireguard/chacha20-poly1305] It's also one of the encryption traffic methods of V2Ray.
[src:wireguard/chacha20-poly1305] ChaCha20-Poly1305 usually offers better performance than the more prevalent AES-GCM algorithm, except on systems where the CPU(s) have the AES-NI instruction set extension.
[src:wireguard/chacha20-poly1305] As a result, ChaCha20-Poly1305 is sometimes preferred over AES-GCM due to its similar levels of security and in certain use cases involving mobile devices, which mostly use ARM-based CPUs.
[src:wireguard/chacha20-poly1305] Because ChaCha20-Poly1305 has less overhead than AES-GCM, ChaCha20-Poly1305 on mobile devices may consume less power than AES-GCM.
[src:wireguard/chacha20-poly1305] The ChaCha20-Poly1305 construction is generally secure in the standard model and the ideal permutation model, for the single- and multi-user setting.
[src:wireguard/chacha20-poly1305] However, similarly to GCM, the security relies on choosing a unique nonce for every message encrypted.
[src:wireguard/chacha20-poly1305] Compared to AES-GCM, implementations of ChaCha20-Poly1305 are less vulnerable to timing attacks.
[src:wireguard/chacha20-poly1305] To be noted, when the SSH protocol uses ChaCha20-Poly1305 as underlying primitive, it is vulnerable to the Terrapin attack.
[src:wireguard/curve25519] In cryptography, **Curve25519** is an elliptic curve used in elliptic-curve cryptography (ECC) offering 128 bits of security (256-bit key size) and designed for use with the Elliptic-curve Diffie–Hellman (ECDH) key agreement scheme, first described and implemented by Daniel J.
[src:wireguard/curve25519] It is one of the fastest curves in ECC, and is not covered by any known patents.
[src:wireguard/curve25519] The reference implementation is public domain software.
[src:wireguard/curve25519] The original Curve25519 paper defined it as a Diffie–Hellman (DH) function.
[src:wireguard/curve25519] Bernstein has since proposed that the name Curve25519 be used for the underlying curve, and the name **X25519** for the DH function.
[src:wireguard/curve25519] The curve used is $y^{2}=x^{3}+486662x^{2}+x$ , a Montgomery curve, over the prime field defined by the pseudo-Mersenne prime number $2^{255}-19$ (hence the numeric "25519" in the name), and it uses the base point $x=9$ .
[src:wireguard/curve25519] This subgroup has a co-factor of 8, meaning the number of elements in the subgroup is ⁠1/8⁠ that of the elliptic curve group.
[src:wireguard/curve25519] Using a prime order subgroup prevents mounting a Pohlig–Hellman algorithm attack.
[src:wireguard/curve25519] The protocol uses compressed elliptic point (only *X* coordinates), so it allows efficient use of the Montgomery ladder for ECDH, using only *XZ* coordinates.
[src:wireguard/curve25519] Curve25519 is constructed such that it avoids many potential implementation pitfalls.
[src:wireguard/curve25519] The curve is birationally equivalent to a twisted Edwards curve used in the Ed25519 signature scheme.
[src:wireguard/curve25519] In 2005, Curve25519 was first released by Daniel J.
[src:wireguard/curve25519] In 2013, interest began to increase considerably when it was discovered that the NSA had potentially implemented a backdoor into the P-256 curve based Dual_EC_DRBG algorithm.
[src:wireguard/curve25519] While not directly related, suspicious aspects of the NIST's P curve constants led to concerns that the NSA had chosen values that gave them an advantage in breaking the encryption.
[src:wireguard/curve25519] Since 2013, Curve25519 has become the *de facto* alternative to P-256, being used in a wide variety of applications.
[src:wireguard/curve25519] Starting in 2014, OpenSSH defaults to Curve25519-based ECDH and GnuPG adds support for Ed25519 keys for signing and encryption.
[src:wireguard/curve25519] The use of the curve was eventually standardized for both key exchange and signature in 2020.
[src:wireguard/curve25519] In 2017, NIST announced that Curve25519 and Curve448 would be added to Special Publication 800-186, which specifies approved elliptic curves for use by the US Federal Government.
[src:wireguard/curve25519] A 2019 draft of "FIPS 186-5" notes the intention to allow usage of Ed25519 for digital signatures.
[src:wireguard/curve25519] The 2023 update of Special Publication 800-186 allows usage of Curve25519.
[src:wireguard/curve25519] In February 2017, the DNSSEC specification for using Ed25519 and Ed448 was published as RFC 8080, assigning algorithm numbers 15 and 16.
[src:wireguard/curve25519] In 2018, DKIM specification was amended so as to allow signatures with this algorithm.
[src:wireguard/curve25519] Also in 2018, RFC 8446 was published as the new Transport Layer Security v1.3 standard.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] The **Noise Protocol Framework**, sometimes referred to as "**Noise**" or "**Noise Framework**", is a public domain cryptographic framework for creating secure communication protocols based on Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] Developed by Trevor Perrin, the framework defines a series of handshake patterns—predefined sequences of message exchanges—that outline how parties initiate communication, exchange keys, and establish shared secrets.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] These patterns can be combined and customized to meet specific security requirements such as mutual authentication, forward secrecy, and identity protection.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] Several popular software applications and protocols, including the messaging platforms WhatsApp and Slack and the VPN protocol WireGuard, have used implementations of the Noise Framework to ensure end-to-end encryption for user communications.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] The framework remains a topic of development, including post-quantum adaptations.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] The framework is currently at revision 34, published in July 2018.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] Most secure channel protocols rely on authenticated key exchange (AKE) using digital signatures (for authentication) and Diffie–Hellman (for key exchange).
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] In the 2000s–2010s, interest grew in developing pure Diffie–Hellman-based AKEs, without signatures, leading to both theoretical (e.g., Kudla-Paterson, NAXOS, Ntor) and practical advancements (e.g., Ntor, NaCl, CurveCP, DNSCurve, OPTLS).
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] These were often developed from scratch.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] Using “sponge-like” symmetric cryptography, inspired by cryptographer Mike Hamburg's Strobe protocol framework.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] The Framework evolved based on work initially conducted at Open Whisper Systems, the software organization from which the Signal Protocol and Signal messaging app originated.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] While unrelated to the signal processing concept of noise, the choice of “Noise” as the name for this cryptographic protocol might be a play on the signal vs. noise concept.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] Originally maintained as a wiki starting from February 10, 2013, the framework's development began with an initial commit to its specification on August 4, 2014.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] The framework evolved through numerous revisions following mailing list discussions until version 34 on July 11, 2018.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] The Noise Protocol Framework acknowledges inspiration from previous cryptographic designs (e.g., NaCl, CurveCP or the KDF chains used in the Double Ratchet Algorithm) and contributions from figures in cryptography and computing (e.g., Jason Donenfeld, Hugo Krawczyk).
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] During its development, the Noise Protocol Framework evolved alongside TLS 1.3, including 2015 discussions comparing the protocols, particularly the “OPTLS” proposal.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] Both projects spanned from 2014 to 2018, with the first draft of TLS 1.3 RFC 8446 released in August 2014 and the final Proposed Standard in August 2018.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] The Noise Framework provided an alternative approach, enabling the selection of specific handshake patterns and cryptographic algorithms to design protocols tailored to specific security properties and performance needs.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] Formal verifications of the Noise Protocol Framework have evaluated its security properties.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] Studies have employed automated tools to model and verify various handshake patterns within the framework, assessing their resilience against a range of attacks.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] The handshake pattern can be described in a diagram as a set of messages, each annotated with a list of tokens that describe cryptographic operations performed on a party's handshake state.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] The line(s) before `...` represent a message prior to DH AKE such as an out-of-band transfer of a public key.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] The specification lists three one-way handshake patterns, and 12 fundamental interactive handshake patterns.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] A real-world example comes from WireGuard whose **Construction** on page 10 of the Whitepaper is `Noise_IKpsk2_25519_ChaChaPoly_BLAKE2s`.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] Each handshake pattern can be combined with one of the 16 combinations of the 8 cryptographic algorithms listed in the Specification.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] As those algorithms are of comparable quality and do not enlarge the design space.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] The implementation of a concrete protocol involves the design of message representation, as well as aspects outside the Noise Framework.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] An example of the latter happens with protocols using UDP transports, such as WireGuard, which uses a sliding window to handle out-of-order arrival.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] Security properties of several handshake patterns are described in the Specification and can support mutual authentication, forward secrecy, zero round-trip encryption, identity hiding, and other advanced features.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] Formal cryptographic analyses of common handshake patterns have appeared in the academic literature.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] The second effort has resulted in the online tool Noise Explorer.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] To produce a Noise Protocol name for `Initialize()` you concatenate the ASCII string `Noise_` with four underscore-separated name sections, which sequentially name the handshake pattern, the DH functions, the cipher functions, and then the hash functions.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] The resulting name must be 255 bytes or less.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] Each name section must consist only of alphanumeric characters (i.e. characters in one of the ranges "A"..."Z", "a"..."z", and "0"..."9"), and the two special characters "+" and "/".
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] Additional rules apply to each name section, as specified below.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] A handshake pattern name section contains a handshake pattern name plus a sequence of zero or more pattern modifiers.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] The handshake pattern name must be an uppercase ASCII string containing only alphabetic characters or numerals (e.g.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] Pattern modifiers specify arbitrary extensions or modifications to the behavior specified by the handshake pattern.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] For example, a modifier could be applied to a handshake pattern, which transforms it into a different pattern according to some rule.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] The `psk0` and `fallback` modifiers are examples of this and will be defined later in this document.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] A pattern modifier is named with a lowercase alphanumeric ASCII string that must begin with an alphabetic character (not a numeral).
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] The first modifier added onto a base pattern is simply appended.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] Thus, the `fallback` modifier, when added to the `XX` pattern, produces `XXfallback`.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] Additional modifiers are separated with a plus sign.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] Thus, adding the `psk0` modifier would result in the name section `XXfallback+psk0`, or a full protocol name such as `Noise_XXfallback+psk0_25519_AESGCM_SHA256`.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] In some cases, the sequential ordering of modifiers will specify different protocols.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] However, if the order of some modifiers does not matter, then they are required to be sorted alphabetically (this is an arbitrary convention to ensure interoperability).
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] The rules for the DH, cipher, and hash name sections are identical.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] Each name section must contain one or more algorithm names separated by plus signs.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] Each algorithm name must consist solely of alphanumeric characters and the forward-slash character ("/").
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] Algorithm names are recommended to be short, and to use the "/" character only when necessary to avoid ambiguity (e.g.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] In most cases, there will be a single algorithm name in each name section (i.e. no plus signs).
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] Multiple algorithm names are only used when called for by the pattern or a modifier.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] None of the patterns or modifiers in this document require multiple algorithm names in any name section.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] However, this functionality might be useful in future extensions.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] For example, multiple algorithm names might be used in the DH section to specify "hybrid" post-quantum forward secrecy; or multiple hash algorithms might be specified for different purposes.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] The Specification lists 8 modern algorithms with the following names.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] The Wiki has this list of unofficial algorithms; I've omitted the Post-Quantum ones as the entries pre-date the NIST Post-Quantum Cryptography Standardization effort starting in 2016 with the first three Post Quantum Crypto Standards: FIPS 203, FIP 204, and FIP 205 in 2024.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] Noise Protocols have a prologue input that allows arbitrary data to be hashed into the h variable.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] If both parties do not provide identical prologue data, the handshake will fail due to a decryption error.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] This is useful when the parties engaged in negotiation prior to the handshake and want to ensure they share identical views of that negotiation.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] For example, suppose Bob communicates to Alice a list of Noise Protocols that he is willing to support.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] Alice will then choose and execute a single protocol.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] To ensure that a "man-in-the-middle" did not edit Bob's list to remove options, Alice and Bob could include the list as prologue data.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] Note that while the parties confirm their prologues are identical, they don't mix prologue data into encryption keys.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] If an input contains secret data that's intended to strengthen the encryption, a PSK handshake should be used instead (see §9).
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] The following handshake patterns represent "one-way" handshakes supporting a one-way stream of data from a sender to a recipient.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] These patterns could be used to encrypt files, database records, or other non-interactive data streams.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] Following a one-way handshake the sender can send a stream of transport messages, encrypting them using the first CipherState returned by `Split()` The second CipherState from `Split()` is discarded - the recipient must not send any messages using it (as this would violate the rules in §7.3).
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] `N` is a conventional DH-based public-key encryption.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] The other patterns add sender authentication, where the sender's public key is either known to the recipient beforehand (`K`) or transmitted under encryption (`X`).
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] The following handshake patterns represent interactive protocols.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] These 12 patterns are called the "fundamental" interactive handshake patterns.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] The first two columns in the table above, prior to each message pattern, lists the security properties for Noise handshake and transport payloads for all the one-way patterns in §7.4 and the fundamental patterns in §7.5.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] Each payload is assigned a "source" property regarding the degree of authentication of the sender provided to the recipient, and a "destination" property regarding the degree of confidentiality provided to the sender.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] The following table lists the identity-hiding properties for all the one-way handshake patterns in §7.4 and the fundamental handshake patterns in §7.5.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] In addition, we list a few deferred handshake patterns which have different identity-hiding properties than the corresponding fundamental pattern.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] Each pattern is assigned properties describing the confidentiality supplied to the initiator's static public key, and to the responder's static public key.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] The underlying assumptions are that ephemeral private keys are secure, and that parties abort the handshake if they receive a static public key from the other party which they don't trust.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] This section only considers identity leakage through static public key fields in handshakes.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] Of course, the identities of Noise participants might be exposed through other means, including payload fields, traffic analysis, or metadata such as IP addresses.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] The fundamental handshake patterns in the previous section perform DH operations for authentication (**es** and **se**) as early as possible.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] An additional set of handshake patterns can be described which defer these authentication DHs to the next message.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] To name these deferred handshake patterns, the numeral `1` is used after the first and/or second character in a fundamental pattern name to indicate that the initiator and/or responder's authentication DH is deferred to the next message.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] Below are two examples showing a fundamental handshake pattern on the left, and deferred variant(s) on the right.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] The full set of 23 deferred handshake patterns are in the Appendix §18.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] So far we've assumed Alice and Bob wish to execute a single Noise Protocol chosen by the initiator (Alice).
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] However, there are a number of reasons why Bob might wish to switch to a different Noise Protocol after receiving Alice's first message.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] Alice might have chosen a Noise Protocol based on a cipher, DH function, or handshake pattern which Bob doesn't support.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] Alice might have sent a "zero-RTT" encrypted initial message based on an out-of-date version of Bob's static public key or PSK.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] Handling these scenarios requires a compound protocol where Bob switches from the initial Noise Protocol chosen by Alice to a new Noise Protocol.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] In such a compound protocol the roles of initiator and responder would be reversed - Bob would become the initiator of the new Noise Protocol, and Alice the responder.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] Compound protocols introduce significant complexity as Alice needs to advertise the Noise Protocol she is beginning with and the Noise Protocol(s) she is capable of switching to, and both parties have to negotiate a secure transition.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] These details are largely out of scope for this document.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] However, to give an example of how compound protocols can be constructed, and to provide some building blocks, the following sections define a fallback modifier and show how it can be used to create a Noise Pipe compound protocol.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] Noise Pipes support the `XX` pattern, but also allow Alice to cache Bob's static public key and attempt an `IK` handshake with 0-RTT encryption.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] In case Bob can't decrypt Alice's initial `IK` message, he will switch to the `XXfallback` pattern, which essentially allows the parties to complete an `XX` handshake as if Alice had sent an `XX` initial message instead of an `IK` initial message.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] The `fallback` modifier converts an Alice-initiated pattern to a Bob-initiated pattern by converting Alice's initial message to a pre-message that Bob must receive through some other means (e.g. via an initial `IK` message from Alice).
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] After this conversion, the rest of the handshake pattern is interpreted as a Bob-initiated handshake pattern.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] Note that fallback can only be applied to handshake patterns in Alice-initiated form where Alice's first message is capable of being interpreted as a pre-message (i.e. it must be either **e**, **s**, or "**e**, **s**").
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] There must be some way for Bob to distinguish the full versus zero-RTT cases on receiving the first message.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] If Alice makes a zero-RTT attempt, there must be some way for her to distinguish the zero-RTT versus switch cases on receiving the response.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] For example, each handshake message could be preceded by some negotiation data, such as a type byte (see §13).
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] This data is not part of the Noise message proper, but signals which Noise Protocol is being used.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] This section defines the Noise Pipe compound protocol.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] The `XX` pattern is used for a full handshake if the parties haven't communicated before, after which Alice can cache Bob's static public key.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] The `IK` pattern is used for a zero-RTT handshake.
[src:wireguard/noise-protocol-framework] The `XXfallback` pattern is used for a switch handshake if Bob fails to decrypt an initial `IK` message (perhaps due to having changed his static key).
[src:wireguard/wireguard] In March 2020, the Linux version of the software reached a stable production release and was incorporated into the Linux 5.6 kernel, and backported to earlier Linux kernels in some Linux distributions.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] The Linux kernel components are licensed under the GNU General Public License (GPL) version 2; other implementations are under GPLv2 or other free/open-source licenses.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] The WireGuard protocol is a variant of the Noise Protocol Framework `IK` handshake pattern.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] The key exchange, or handshake, combines long-term and ephemeral Diffie-Hellman values using Curve25519.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] Each pair generates a set of public and private key pairs using Curve 25519, the public keys are exchanged, with each pair then assigned an IP address (generally RFC 1918) to utilize with the WireGuard tunnel.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] Once the keys have been confirmed by both peers, the Noise Protocol is used to generate a shared ChaCha20 session key for symmetric encryption authenticated with Poly1305.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] SipHash24 is used for hashtable keys while BLAKE2s cryptographic hash functions, a faster and more compact version of SHA-3, are incorporated.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] Key derivation functions are handled using HKDF and Base64-encoded private keys, public keys and preshared keys.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] WireGuard’s proof starts by modeling its two-message Noise-based handshake (plus optional PSK) in CryptoVerif’s calculus of cryptographic games, abstracting ChaCha20-Poly1305, Curve25519, HKDF, the hash chain, and related primitives under standard IND-CPA/INT-CTXT and random-oracle assumptions.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] From that model, CryptoVerif’s automated game hops show, across unlimited parallel sessions, that the protocol guarantees mutual authentication, IND-CCA session-key secrecy, forward secrecy and post-compromise security even if long-term keys later leak and state is wiped.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] In May 2019, researchers from INRIA published a machine-checked proof of the WireGuard protocol, produced using the CryptoVerif proof assistant.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] WireGuard supports pre-shared symmetric key mode, which provides an additional layer of symmetric encryption to mitigate future advances in quantum computing.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] This addresses the risk that traffic may be stored until quantum computers are capable of breaking Curve25519, at which point traffic could be decrypted.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] Pre-shared keys are "usually troublesome from a key management perspective and might be more likely stolen", but in the shorter term, if the symmetric key is compromised, the Curve25519 keys still provide more than sufficient protection.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] WireGuard uses only UDP, due to the potential disadvantages of TCP-over-TCP.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] Tunneling TCP over a TCP-based connection can induce a dramatic loss in transmission performance due to the TCP meltdown problem.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] WireGuard fully supports IPv6, both inside and outside of tunnel.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] It supports only layer 3 for both IPv4 and IPv6 and can encapsulate v4-in-v6 and vice versa.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] Assuming the underlay network transporting the WireGuard packets maintains a 1500 byte MTU, configuring the WireGuard interface to 1420 bytes MTU for all involved peers is ideal for being transported over IPv6 + IPv4.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] However, when exclusively utilizing legacy IPv4 transport, a higher MTU of 1440 bytes for the WireGuard interface suffices.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] From an operational perspective and for network configuration uniformity, leaving the default 1420 byte MTU network-wide for the WireGuard interfaces would be advantageous.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] This approach ensures consistency and facilitates a smoother transition to enabling IPv6 for the WireGuard peers and interfaces in the future.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] Hosts often avoid sending packets > 1280 due to PMTUD reliability.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] The MTU of a WireGuard interface is determined by the encapsulating, or *outer*, IP protocol—not the IP version carried inside the tunnel.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] When WireGuard packets are transported over IPv4, the outer-header overhead is 60 bytes (20-byte IPv4 header, 8-byte UDP header, and 32-byte WireGuard header).
[src:wireguard/wireguard] When transported over IPv6, the outer-header overhead rises to 80 bytes.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] This distinction means that even if a peer is reachable only via IPv4, other peers in the same mesh may connect over IPv6 or through translation mechanisms.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] Translation increases header size and enforces IPv6’s 1280-byte minimum path MTU, requiring that implementers budget for the 80-byte IPv6 overhead when setting a consistent interface MTU.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] WireGuard is designed to be extended by third-party programs and scripts.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] This has been used to augment WireGuard with various features including more user-friendly management interfaces (including easier setting up of keys), logging, dynamic firewall updates, dynamic IP assignment, and LDAP integration.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] It is supported natively and by a number of commercial VPN services such as NordVPN, IPVanish, Mullvad, and TunnelBear.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] One WireGuard-based fork, AmneziaWG, adds traffic-obfuscation mechanisms intended to make WireGuard traffic less identifiable to deep packet inspection systems.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] Excluding such complex features from the minimal core codebase improves its stability and security.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] For ensuring security, WireGuard restricts the options for implementing cryptographic controls, limits the choices for key exchange processes, and maps algorithms to a small subset of modern cryptographic primitives.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] If a flaw is found in any of the primitives, a new version can be released that resolves the issue.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] A review by *Ars Technica* found that WireGuard was easy to set up and use, used strong ciphers, and had a minimal codebase that provided for a small attack surface.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] A 2024 report concluded that WireGuard had potential as a lightweight robust solution for Internet of things security.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] WireGuard has received funding from the Open Technology Fund and donations from *Jump Trading*, Mullvad, Tailscale, *Fly.io*, and the NLnet Foundation.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] Oregon senator Ron Wyden has recommended to the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) that they evaluate WireGuard as a replacement for existing technologies.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] Early snapshots of the code base exist from 30 June 2016.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] The logo is inspired by a stone engraving of the mythological Python that Jason Donenfeld saw while visiting a museum in Delphi.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] On 9 December 2019, David Miller – primary maintainer of the Linux networking stack – accepted the WireGuard patches into the "net-next" maintainer tree, for inclusion in an upcoming kernel.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] On 28 January 2020, Linus Torvalds merged David Miller's net-next tree, and WireGuard entered the mainline Linux kernel tree.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] On 20 March 2020, Debian developers enabled the module build options for WireGuard in their kernel config for the Debian 11 version (testing).
[src:wireguard/wireguard] On 29 March 2020 WireGuard was incorporated into the Linux 5.6 release tree.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] The Windows version of the software remains at beta.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] This led to Android developers adding native kernel support for WireGuard in their Generic Kernel Image on 30 March 2020.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] On 22 April 2020, NetworkManager developer Beniamino Galvani merged GUI support for WireGuard in GNOME.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] On 12 May 2020, Matt Dunwoodie proposed patches for native kernel support of WireGuard in OpenBSD.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] On 22 June 2020, after the work of Matt Dunwoodie and Jason A.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] Donenfeld, WireGuard support was imported into OpenBSD.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] Donenfeld released an update of the Windows package improving installation, stability, ARM support, and enterprise features.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] On 29 November 2020, WireGuard support was imported into the FreeBSD 13 kernel.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] On 19 January 2021, WireGuard support was added for preview in pfSense Community Edition (CE) 2.5.0 development snapshots.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] In March 2021, kernel-mode WireGuard support was removed from FreeBSD 13.0, still in testing, after an urgent code cleanup in FreeBSD WireGuard could not be completed quickly.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] FreeBSD-based pfSense Community Edition (CE) 2.5.0 and pfSense Plus 21.02 removed kernel-based WireGuard as well.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] In May 2021, WireGuard support was re-introduced back into pfSense CE and pfSense Plus development snapshots as an experimental package written by a member of the pfSense community, Christian McDonald.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] The WireGuard package for pfSense incorporates the ongoing kernel-mode WireGuard development work by Jason A.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] Donenfeld that was originally sponsored by Netgate.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] In June 2021, the official package repositories for both pfSense CE 2.5.2 and pfSense Plus 21.05 included the WireGuard package.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] In 2023, WireGuard received over 209,000€ support from Germany's Sovereign Tech Fund.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] In June 2025, IPFire has added support for WireGuard using the Linux kernel implementation.
[src:wireguard/wireguard] In January 2026 Iran International reported that WireGuard was being used in Iran in the aftermath of the 2026 Iran protests, albeit with limited success.
